[1] Liberia (Margibi)
Date: Mon 13 Apr 2015
Source: New Dawn [abridged & edited]
http://www.thenewdawnliberia.com/news/7133-measles-kills-6-in-margibi


As Margibi County observes the absence of Ebola for more than 42 days without a new case, another disease has hit the county, killing at least 6 people. Speaking to reporters in Kakata, Margibi County on Friday [10 Apr 2015], the County Mobilization Coordinator for UNICEF, Sophie Reeves, disclosed that there are about 77 measles cases with 6 deaths reported in the county.

Madam Reeves, who also works with the Margibi County Health Team, explained that cases, which are found within the 4 health districts of Margibi, including Gibi, Mahnban Kaba, Marshall and Kakata, erupted 2 weeks ago, with Gibi district being highly hit by the disease. She described the outbreak as very scary and urged the people of Margibi to be very careful before the chain transmission rapidly increases in the county. Madam Reeves stressed that a single measles case should be considered an outbreak because it spreads too fast like a wide fire among the population.

Meanwhile, she noted that due to the nature of the cases in Gibi District, the county health team and its partners have decided to urgently take measles vaccine to Gibi ahead of the nationwide vaccination period set for 8-14 May 2015. According to her, the county health team and partners will today, Mon Apr 13 2015, take the measles vaccine to Gibi District. She warns that if the county health team does not reach the district now, more deaths could occur because Gibi is highly hit.

Madam Reeves has, meanwhile, warned the people of Margibi to refrain from calling the measles vaccine an Ebola vaccine, something, which noted, has already started to make many people afraid to take the vaccine.

Measles vaccine will target children between 6-59 months, or less than 5 years, while the polio vaccine will target 0-59 months, or under 5 years, and the worm tablets will target children 1-5 years old.

[byline: Ramsey N Singbeh, Jr]

